    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Hallucination detection determines whether an LLM's output contains claims that are unsupported, false, or inconsistent with a given source. Methods fall into three families: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "reference-based",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (compare output to a known-correct document), "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "reference-free",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (detect uncertainty from the model itself), and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLM-as-judge",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (use another model to verify claims)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Hallucination detection taxonomy: reference-based, reference-free, and LLM-as-judge approaches"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reference-Based Detection"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reference-based methods require a trusted document \u2014 a retrieved passage, a ground-truth answer, or a knowledge base entry \u2014 against which the model output is checked. They offer high precision but cannot be used when no reference exists."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "NLI Entailment Check"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Natural Language Inference (NLI) classifies whether a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "hypothesis",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (the model claim) is entailed by, neutral to, or contradicts a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "premise",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (the reference). A contradiction label indicates a potential hallucination:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import pipeline\n\nnli = pipeline(\n    'text-classification',\n    model='cross-encoder/nli-deberta-v3-small',\n)\n\ndef entailment_score(premise: str, hypothesis: str) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Returns {'ENTAILMENT': p, 'NEUTRAL': p, 'CONTRADICTION': p}.\"\"\"\n    result = nli(f'{premise} [SEP] {hypothesis}')[0]\n    return {r['label']: r['score'] for r in nli(\n        {'text': premise, 'text_pair': hypothesis},\n        top_k=3,\n    )}\n\ndef is_hallucination(premise: str, claim: str, threshold: float = 0.5) -> bool:\n    scores = entailment_score(premise, claim)\n    return scores.get('CONTRADICTION', 0) > threshold"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "FactScore: Atomic Fact Decomposition"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "FactScore (Min et al., 2023) breaks a long generation into atomic facts (single-claim sentences), retrieves evidence for each, then labels each fact as supported or unsupported:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\nDECOMPOSE_SYSTEM = '''\nBreak the given text into a list of atomic facts.\nEach fact must be a single, independently verifiable claim.\nOutput JSON: {\"facts\": [\"...\", ...]}\n'''\n\ndef decompose_into_facts(text: str) -> list[str]:\n    resp = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model='claude-haiku-4-5-20251001',\n        messages=[\n            {'role': 'system', 'content': DECOMPOSE_SYSTEM},\n            {'role': 'user', 'content': text},\n        ],\n        response_format={'type': 'json_object'},\n    )\n    import json\n    return json.loads(resp.choices[0].message.content)['facts']\n\nVERIFY_SYSTEM = '''\nGiven a passage and a claim, answer: is the claim supported by the passage?\nOutput JSON: {\"supported\": true/false, \"reason\": \"...\"}\n'''\n\ndef verify_fact(passage: str, fact: str) -> dict:\n    resp = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model='claude-haiku-4-5-20251001',\n        messages=[\n            {'role': 'system', 'content': VERIFY_SYSTEM},\n            {'role': 'user', 'content': f'Passage: {passage}\\n\\nClaim: {fact}'},\n        ],\n        response_format={'type': 'json_object'},\n    )\n    import json\n    return json.loads(resp.choices[0].message.content)\n\ndef factscore(generation: str, evidence_passage: str) -> float:\n    \"\"\"Fraction of atomic facts supported by the evidence.\"\"\"\n    facts = decompose_into_facts(generation)\n    if not facts:\n        return 1.0\n    results = [verify_fact(evidence_passage, f) for f in facts]\n    supported = sum(1 for r in results if r['supported'])\n    return supported / len(facts)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reference-Free Detection"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reference-free methods detect hallucinations without any ground truth. They exploit a key property: facts that an LLM knows well will be reproduced consistently across multiple independent samples, while fabricated claims will vary or conflict across samples."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Self-Consistency Sampling"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sample the same question N times with non-zero temperature. Count how often each answer appears. Low-consensus answers are likely hallucinations:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from collections import Counter\nfrom openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\ndef self_consistency(\n    question: str,\n    n_samples: int = 10,\n    temperature: float = 0.8,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Sample answer N times, return most-common answer and confidence.\n    High confidence = answer repeated consistently (likely factual).\n    Low confidence = diverse answers (likely hallucinated / uncertain).\n    \"\"\"\n    answers = []\n    for _ in range(n_samples):\n        resp = client.chat.completions.create(\n            model='claude-haiku-4-5-20251001',\n            messages=[{'role': 'user', 'content': question}],\n            temperature=temperature,\n            max_tokens=60,\n        )\n        answers.append(resp.choices[0].message.content.strip())\n    counter = Counter(answers)\n    best_answer, count = counter.most_common(1)[0]\n    confidence = count / n_samples\n    return {\n        'answer': best_answer,\n        'confidence': confidence,\n        'is_hallucination': confidence < 0.4,  # tunable threshold\n        'all_answers': dict(counter),\n    }"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Semantic Entropy"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Self-consistency uses exact-match voting, which fails when paraphrases express the same meaning. Semantic entropy (Kuhn et al., 2023) clusters answers by semantic equivalence first, then measures entropy over clusters:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\ndef embed(texts: list[str]) -> np.ndarray:\n    resp = client.embeddings.create(\n        model='text-embedding-3-small',\n        input=texts,\n    )\n    return np.array([e.embedding for e in resp.data])\n\ndef semantic_entropy(answers: list[str], sim_threshold: float = 0.92) -> float:\n    \"\"\"\n    1. Embed all answers.\n    2. Cluster by cosine similarity (greedy).\n    3. Compute entropy over cluster sizes.\n    High entropy = diverse meanings = likely hallucination.\n    \"\"\"\n    if len(answers) <= 1:\n        return 0.0\n    embs = embed(answers)\n    norms = embs / np.linalg.norm(embs, axis=1, keepdims=True)\n    # Greedy clustering\n    clusters = []\n    assigned = [False] * len(answers)\n    for i in range(len(answers)):\n        if assigned[i]:\n            continue\n        cluster = [i]\n        assigned[i] = True\n        for j in range(i + 1, len(answers)):\n            if not assigned[j]:\n                sim = float(norms[i] @ norms[j])\n                if sim >= sim_threshold:\n                    cluster.append(j)\n                    assigned[j] = True\n        clusters.append(cluster)\n    # Shannon entropy over cluster sizes\n    probs = np.array([len(c) for c in clusters]) / len(answers)\n    entropy = -np.sum(probs * np.log(probs + 1e-9))\n    return float(entropy)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "A semantic entropy of 0 means all answers cluster into one meaning \u2014 high confidence. An entropy above ~1.5 nats (with 10 samples) suggests genuine uncertainty and likely hallucination."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Token Probability as a Proxy"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When the model has white-box access (open-weight models), token log-probabilities are a fast hallucination signal. Spans with unusually low probability are candidates for factual errors:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nfrom transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForCausalLM\n\ndef low_prob_spans(\n    model_name: str,\n    prompt: str,\n    response: str,\n    threshold: float = -3.0,  # log-prob below this = suspicious\n) -> list[str]:\n    tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_name)\n    model = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(model_name)\n    model.eval()\n    full_text = prompt + response\n    inputs = tokenizer(full_text, return_tensors='pt')\n    prompt_len = len(tokenizer(prompt)['input_ids'])\n    with torch.no_grad():\n        outputs = model(**inputs)\n    log_probs = torch.log_softmax(outputs.logits[0], dim=-1)\n    input_ids = inputs['input_ids'][0]\n    suspicious = []\n    for i in range(prompt_len, len(input_ids) - 1):\n        token_id = input_ids[i + 1].item()\n        lp = log_probs[i, token_id].item()\n        if lp < threshold:\n            suspicious.append(tokenizer.decode([token_id]))\n    return suspicious"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLM-as-Judge for Hallucination"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A powerful LLM can be used as a claim verifier. The pattern: decompose the response into claims, optionally retrieve evidence, then prompt the judge to evaluate each claim's factuality."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Claim Verification Pipeline"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom openai import OpenAI\nimport json\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\n@dataclass\nclass ClaimVerdict:\n    claim: str\n    verdict: str          # 'supported' | 'refuted' | 'unverifiable'\n    evidence: str\n    confidence: float\n\nVERIFIER_SYSTEM = '''\nYou are a fact-checking assistant.\nGiven a claim and optional context, determine if the claim is:\n  - supported: the claim is correct\n  - refuted: the claim is factually wrong\n  - unverifiable: cannot determine without more information\nOutput JSON: {\"verdict\": \"...\", \"evidence\": \"...\", \"confidence\": 0.0-1.0}\n'''\n\ndef verify_claim(\n    claim: str,\n    context: str = '',\n) -> ClaimVerdict:\n    user_msg = f'Claim: {claim}'\n    if context:\n        user_msg = f'Context: {context}\\n\\n{user_msg}'\n    resp = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model='claude-sonnet-4-6',\n        messages=[\n            {'role': 'system', 'content': VERIFIER_SYSTEM},\n            {'role': 'user', 'content': user_msg},\n        ],\n        response_format={'type': 'json_object'},\n    )\n    data = json.loads(resp.choices[0].message.content)\n    return ClaimVerdict(\n        claim=claim,\n        verdict=data['verdict'],\n        evidence=data['evidence'],\n        confidence=data['confidence'],\n    )\n\ndef hallucination_report(generation: str, context: str = '') -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Full pipeline: decompose \u2192 verify each claim.\"\"\"\",\n    facts = decompose_into_facts(generation)  # from FactScore section\n    verdicts = [verify_claim(f, context) for f in facts]\n    refuted = [v for v in verdicts if v.verdict == 'refuted']\n    return {\n        'total_claims': len(verdicts),\n        'refuted': len(refuted),\n        'hallucination_rate': len(refuted) / max(len(verdicts), 1),\n        'details': [{'claim': v.claim, 'verdict': v.verdict} for v in verdicts],\n    }"
          }
        ]
      },
